00:49:09,009 --> 00:49:12,369
she will argue with me and
make my life look pitiful.

707
00:49:12,409 --> 00:49:14,809
That's marriage.

708
00:49:14,889 --> 00:49:19,089
- How are you?
- Hey, how's the baby?

709
00:49:24,250 --> 00:49:26,409
Guys!
Hi, guys!

710
00:49:27,889 --> 00:49:33,289
Well, I'll be home around 6:30.
Want me to pick up anything?

711
00:49:33,369 --> 00:49:36,209
Oh no, that sounds good.
No, no, I like that. Okay, great.

712
00:49:36,289 --> 00:49:39,089
Okay, bye, honey.
Gwen!

713
00:50:24,449 --> 00:50:26,729
- May I talk with you?
- Um...

714
00:50:26,809 --> 00:50:31,249
I just had a big fight with Gwen.
I came home from work and she started...

715
00:50:31,329 --> 00:50:34,049
I'm sorry, I shouldn't
even be talking about it.

716
00:50:34,129 --> 00:50:37,329
No, it's just... Uh, come in.
Come in, please.

717
00:50:37,409 --> 00:50:39,849
I don't know how
I ended up here.

718
00:50:39,929 --> 00:50:42,889
I just walked away from the house
not thinking about where I was going.

719
00:50:42,969 --> 00:50:45,929
My thoughts were chaotic.
I saw the light in your window.

720
00:50:46,009 --> 00:50:50,609
- Davis, Gwen is here.
- She is?

721
00:50:50,689 --> 00:50:53,810
- You bet I am.
- What are you doing here?

722
00:50:53,889 --> 00:50:55,769
No, what are you
doing here?

723
00:50:55,809 --> 00:50:56,369
Oh God.

724
00:50:56,369 --> 00:50:59,449
- I am trying so hard to make
this marriage work.

725
00:50:59,529 --> 00:51:01,209
Oh, that is rich!

726
00:51:01,289 --> 00:51:04,809
- Rich?
- Guys, please.

727
00:51:04,889 --> 00:51:07,530
She promised she would
never see him again.

728
00:51:07,569 --> 00:51:09,450
Oh, it's my fault.

729
00:51:09,489 --> 00:51:13,290
Ask Mr. Matrimony when the
last time we slept together was.

730
00:51:13,369 --> 00:51:18,090
- What?
- You wanna tell her the truth?

731
00:51:18,169 --> 00:51:21,969
- Really?
- Once.

732
00:51:22,049 --> 00:51:25,529
Once in I don't want to tell you
how long. You want to tell her why?

733
00:51:25,609 --> 00:51:27,049
Me?

734
00:51:27,129 --> 00:51:32,289
Because our Mr. Davis
lives with a little, dark secret.

735
00:51:35,969 --> 00:51:38,689
Hey, really, I don't
want to get involved.

736
00:51:38,769 --> 00:51:43,330
Oh, but you are involved.
You're the secret.

737
00:51:43,409 --> 00:51:45,849
Oh, he's tried to
overcome it, God love him.

738
00:51:45,930 --> 00:51:50,369
He's tried to forget about you. For a time,
I thought we were really gonna make it.

739
00:51:50,449 --> 00:51:54,249
You felt so close to me then.
We used to wash each other's hair.

740
00:51:54,329 --> 00:51:56,889
Everything was
just so perfect.

741
00:51:56,969 --> 00:51:59,930
And then came Maui.

742
00:52:01,209 --> 00:52:03,449
What happened
in Maui?

743
00:52:06,569 --> 00:52:09,530
Uh, well...

744
00:52:09,609 --> 00:52:13,090
Gwen might as well
tell it.

745
00:52:14,129 --> 00:52:17,890
We went there to
celebrate his promotion.

746
00:52:17,969 --> 00:52:22,369
He was so happy then, almost too happy.
He was working so hard...

747
00:52:22,449 --> 00:52:24,890
to have fun
and please me.

748
00:52:24,969 --> 00:52:29,089
He'd chase me into the surf
and carry me into the cabana.

749
00:52:29,129 --> 00:52:30,930
He'd dance
and we'd drink.

750
00:52:30,969 --> 00:52:34,649
He'd toss nuts in the air
and catch them in his mouth,

751
00:52:34,689 --> 00:52:38,689
breaking his tooth so we had to spend
the last day of our vacation...

752
00:52:38,769 --> 00:52:42,089
Iooking for a dentist
to do an emergency crown.

753
00:52:42,170 --> 00:52:45,929
I'll never forget holding his hand
in that dentist's chair,

754
00:52:45,969 --> 00:52:48,969
waiting for him to wake up
from the gas they'd given him.

755
00:52:49,049 --> 00:52:52,849
He had that cotton
sticking out of his mouth.

756
00:52:52,929 --> 00:52:57,209
When he gazed up at me,
he said:

757
00:52:58,809 --> 00:53:00,649
"Becky.

758
00:53:02,890 --> 00:53:06,569
Oh, Becky."

759
00:53:11,449 --> 00:53:14,489
I came here tonight because
when you walked out that door...

760
00:53:14,529 --> 00:53:18,809
I had to see if this is
where you were gonna go.

761
00:53:21,929 --> 00:53:24,169
Gwen!

762
00:53:29,969 --> 00:53:32,449
- What are we gonna do?
- Oh, Davis.

763
00:53:34,929 --> 00:53:37,849
Hey, hey, hey!

764
00:53:37,929 --> 00:53:40,769
That was great. She's definitely
starting to come around.

765
00:53:40,849 --> 00:53:42,729
- Thank you.
- Just doing my job.

766
00:53:42,769 --> 00:53:45,810
- Did you come up with that
on the spur of the moment?

767
00:53:45,810 --> 00:53:46,249
Yeah.

768
00:53:46,329 --> 00:53:50,610
Wow! You're a genius. You're like
the Ernest Hemingway of bullshit.

769
00:53:50,689 --> 00:53:52,689
Really, you're like
a living work of art.

770
00:53:52,729 --> 00:53:55,049
- Oh, God, I don't...
- What?

771
00:53:55,129 --> 00:53:57,689
Thank you.

772
00:54:02,129 --> 00:54:05,570
This is not something we want
to force on you by any means.

773
00:54:05,609 --> 00:54:09,649
We'd like you to consider
a little reception.

774
00:54:09,729 --> 00:54:12,129
- A what?
- People have been coming up to us...

775
00:54:12,209 --> 00:54:15,369
now that
the word is out,

776
00:54:15,450 --> 00:54:17,729
and asking
what they should do...

777
00:54:17,770 --> 00:54:19,649
in terms of gifts.

778
00:54:19,729 --> 00:54:23,049
- Gifts?
- No, no, no. No gifts.

779
00:54:23,089 --> 00:54:26,049
We're not talking
anything lavish.

780
00:54:26,129 --> 00:54:28,729
Would this be that I could,
like, go register?

781
00:54:28,809 --> 00:54:30,729
Certainly.
We could go together.

782
00:54:30,769 --> 00:54:32,730
- Sweetheart?
- Yes, honeybun?

783
00:54:32,769 --> 00:54:35,529
Don't you think a reception
is a horrible idea?

784
00:54:35,569 --> 00:54:38,289
No.

785
00:54:38,369 --> 00:54:42,489
Our marriage is in
a very ambiguous state.

786
00:54:42,529 --> 00:54:46,649
Which is why your mother and I agree
that it might be what the doctor ordered.

787
00:54:46,729 --> 00:54:50,010
- Give it a fresh start.
- I think you're right.

788
00:54:50,049 --> 00:54:53,489
Another thing, unless
this makes you uncomfortable,

789
00:54:53,570 --> 00:54:55,609
I'd like for you
to call me "Dad."

790
00:54:55,689 --> 00:54:59,289
Newton?

791
00:55:01,250 --> 00:55:05,049
No, it wouldn't make me
feel uncomfortable at all...

792
00:55:05,129 --> 00:55:06,809
Dad.

793
00:55:12,249 --> 00:55:14,929
Shall we?

794
00:55:15,009 --> 00:55:18,089
Let me lay out
our thinking here.

795
00:55:18,169 --> 00:55:21,489
Uncles, aunts, cousins,
Gwen's parents...

796
00:55:21,569 --> 00:55:24,489
and any siblings or other relatives
who'd like to come.

797
00:55:24,570 --> 00:55:28,649
- We'd be delighted to have them.
- This is out of control.

798
00:55:28,729 --> 00:55:31,570
A marriage is bigger
than two people.

799
00:55:31,649 --> 00:55:33,969
We don't have
to invite her family.

800
00:55:34,049 --> 00:55:38,089
Newton, we'd like to meet them.
They're our family too.

801
00:55:38,169 --> 00:55:41,889
Well...

802
00:55:41,969 --> 00:55:44,009
Gwen's parents
are divorced.

803
00:55:44,089 --> 00:55:46,569
What's more,
they hate each other.

804
00:55:46,609 --> 00:55:50,969
If you get the two of them
in the same room, it's bedlam.

805
00:55:51,050 --> 00:55:54,330
Am I right?

806
00:55:54,409 --> 00:55:58,129
Oh, you poor thing.
I'm so sorry.

807
00:55:58,170 --> 00:56:01,809
I don't think a reception
would be wise.

808
00:56:01,890 --> 00:56:05,249
No!

809
00:56:05,329 --> 00:56:08,449
You're angry,
aren't you?

810
00:56:08,529 --> 00:56:12,009
- I am not angry.
- You're acting like you're angry.

811
00:56:12,049 --> 00:56:14,249
I'm fine, okay?
Can we drop it?

812
00:56:14,329 --> 00:56:17,369
- What would you have done?
- Davis, I'm not arguing with you.

813
00:56:17,449 --> 00:56:21,490
They're divorced and they
hate each other's guts, fine!

814
00:56:21,569 --> 00:56:23,690
I've broken this line,

815
00:56:23,769 --> 00:56:27,569
cantilevered the rafters and
run the truss joist this way...

816
00:56:27,649 --> 00:56:29,929
and turned a negative
into a positive.

817
00:56:30,009 --> 00:56:33,409
It is so depressing to work
alongside someone of your caliber.

818
00:56:33,489 --> 00:56:36,489
- When did you come up with this?
- This morning or last night.

819
00:56:36,569 --> 00:56:37,769
You've been here all night?

820
00:56:37,769 --> 00:56:39,849
- Becky thinks
I've already got this promotion.

821
00:56:39,889 --> 00:56:42,449
- You told her that?
- Gwen did.

822
00:56:42,529 --> 00:56:44,729
So, can you
show this to Moseby?

823
00:56:44,810 --> 00:56:46,730
- You better do it.
- Why? He likes you!

824
00:56:46,769 --> 00:56:50,729
If I take that in there and Moseby starts
carrying on about how brilliant it is,

825
00:56:50,809 --> 00:56:52,889
I'm going to take
the credit.

826
00:56:52,969 --> 00:56:55,089
- What?
- Mm-hmm.

827
00:56:55,129 --> 00:56:57,489
You're my friend.
Where're your ethics?

828
00:56:57,570 --> 00:57:01,410
My ethics are that
I know this about myself...

829
00:57:01,489 --> 00:57:04,169
so I'm not going to take
this in and screw you over.

830
00:57:04,209 --> 00:57:06,409
Mr. Sharpstein!

831
00:57:12,729 --> 00:57:16,009
Do you think Mr. Moseby
might see me?

832
00:57:16,089 --> 00:57:18,849
Let me check.

833
00:57:22,569 --> 00:57:27,129
Mr. Davis from the third
floor to see you.

834
00:57:27,209 --> 00:57:31,369
Okay.
Go right on in.

835
00:57:31,449 --> 00:57:33,890
- Really?
- Mm-hmm.

836
00:57:35,209 --> 00:57:37,169
Thank you.

837
00:57:39,129 --> 00:57:42,969
- Davis! You're in a lot of trouble.
- Mr. Moseby.

838
00:57:43,049 --> 00:57:43,609
I am?

839
00:57:43,609 --> 00:57:47,409
- How the hell come
I never knew you were married?

840
00:57:47,489 --> 00:57:49,889
Hi, honey.

841
00:57:49,969 --> 00:57:52,849
If this little gal
hadn't wandered to the wrong floor...

842
00:57:52,889 --> 00:57:56,810
Davis, when one of our young people gets
married, I want to be the first to know,

843
00:57:56,889 --> 00:58:00,090
especially when his wife
and I have so much in common.

844
00:58:00,169 --> 00:58:04,809
We just figured out Gwen's dad and I
fought in the same outfit in the Pacific.

845
00:58:04,890 --> 00:58:07,969
- Really?
- Isn't that incredible?

846
00:58:08,009 --> 00:58:12,089
Not half as incredible as the
story of meeting the Dunckles.

847
00:58:12,170 --> 00:58:14,809
- The who?
- Her parents.

848
00:58:14,889 --> 00:58:20,289
- Oh! Yeah, gosh, was that ever funny.
- You thought it was funny?

849
00:58:20,369 --> 00:58:23,130
It was funny at first.
There was that incident.

850
00:58:23,169 --> 00:58:26,010
Which made me so angry.

851
00:58:26,049 --> 00:58:29,649
- Yes, but I can explain.
- Shake my hand.

852
00:58:29,689 --> 00:58:31,770
You brought that man
back to life.

853
00:58:31,849 --> 00:58:35,169
You're an extraordinary
human being.

854
00:58:35,249 --> 00:58:38,889
Well, he's just such a great guy,
Gwen's dad.

855
00:58:38,969 --> 00:58:42,009
What's Gwen's dad
got to do with it?

856
00:58:42,089 --> 00:58:44,130
I'm talking
about your dad...

857
00:58:44,209 --> 00:58:47,849
when you sang,
"Too-ra-loo-ra-loo-ral" to him,

858
00:58:47,889 --> 00:58:51,569
bringing tears
to his eyes.

859
00:58:51,649 --> 00:58:54,929
Damn, Davis, there's more
to you than meets the eye.

860
00:58:54,969 --> 00:58:57,970
And you always seemed
a strange duck.

861
00:58:58,049 --> 00:59:01,729
- That's because he's a swan, Mr. Moseby.
- Listen to her.

862
00:59:01,810 --> 00:59:05,009
Honey, how come you never invited
Mr. Moseby over to the house?

863
00:59:05,049 --> 00:59:07,409
My hubby designed the most
beautiful little house.

864
00:59:07,489 --> 00:59:08,849
He did now?

865
00:59:08,849 --> 00:59:12,529
I've got the perfect idea.
The reception.

866
00:59:12,569 --> 00:59:15,089
Saturday afternoon,
nothing fancy,

867
00:59:15,169 --> 00:59:17,089
just family
and friends over.

868
00:59:17,170 --> 00:59:20,449
Oh, I don't want
to impose.

869
00:59:20,529 --> 00:59:23,490
No imposition at all,
Winston.

870
00:59:23,569 --> 00:59:26,370
And wait until you see
this house he designed!

871
00:59:26,449 --> 00:59:28,889
It's particularly great
for entertaining.

872
00:59:28,970 --> 00:59:32,130
But you're going to be
with your relatives!

873
00:59:33,889 --> 00:59:36,930
Yeah, like, like, like
Gwen's dad.

874
00:59:36,969 --> 00:59:39,649
They're driving in from Toledo
and I'd love to show you the house.

875
00:59:39,729 --> 00:59:42,849
You and Gwen's dad
can catch up on old times.

876
00:59:42,929 --> 00:59:45,489
Well, sounds good.

877
00:59:50,729 --> 00:59:55,170
This is so fantastic! I can't believe
you came to help me get this promotion.

878
00:59:55,209 --> 00:59:57,489
This is above and beyond.
Gwen, you're amazing.

879
00:59:57,529 --> 01:00:00,649
- Did you notice how I picked up your cue?
- Yeah.

880
01:00:00,729 --> 01:00:04,049
This is so interesting,
like, your last name is Dunckle.

881
01:00:04,090 --> 01:00:08,489
- I never knew your last name.
- It's Buckley.

882
01:00:08,569 --> 01:00:11,169
- Well, technically my husband's name.
- You're married?

883
01:00:11,209 --> 01:00:14,449
- Was.
- So Dunckle is your maiden name?

884
01:00:14,489 --> 01:00:16,889
Sort of.
It was my mom's name.

885
01:00:16,969 --> 01:00:19,569
Maybe my dad's,
he was never in the picture.

886
01:00:19,649 --> 01:00:23,369
Who do you consider your parents?
Let me put it this way.

887
01:00:23,409 --> 01:00:26,609
Who's the guy in Toledo who watched "Howdy
Doody" and served in the South Pacific?

888
01:00:26,689 --> 01:00:28,529
An invention!

889
01:00:32,409 --> 01:00:35,090
The problem is
you stink at lying.

890
01:00:35,129 --> 01:00:37,290
- Every time you try,
you get us into trouble.

891
01:00:37,290 --> 01:00:38,689
Forgive me, o queen of crap.

892
01:00:38,769 --> 01:00:41,289
- The problem is,
you don't have any parents.

893
01:00:41,289 --> 01:00:42,809
No, I don't have parents.

894
01:00:42,889 --> 01:00:46,569
- Did they pass away?
- I don't know.

895
01:00:46,649 --> 01:00:49,569
Don't worry,
I'll get some.

896
01:00:57,129 --> 01:01:00,289
We are so pleased
about the reception.

897
01:01:00,369 --> 01:01:03,929
Your folks are coming to town.
You two are getting along.

898
01:01:04,009 --> 01:01:07,209
- We like to think we had a hand in that.
- Oh look!

899
01:01:07,289 --> 01:01:09,689
- It looks like something
Granny would have.

900
01:01:09,689 --> 01:01:10,969
That's a nice pattern.

901
01:01:11,049 --> 01:01:13,129
- Nice?
- What about this?

902
01:01:13,169 --> 01:01:16,209
That I like!
That's us.

903
01:01:17,849 --> 01:01:20,569
- Excuse me.
- Yes.

904
01:01:25,169 --> 01:01:28,409
I suggested
we have the reception.

905
01:01:28,450 --> 01:01:31,289
A marriage is bigger
than two people.

906
01:01:31,330 --> 01:01:34,569
I just want to do everything
I can to save it.

907
01:01:34,649 --> 01:01:38,409
You're such a great husband, Davis.

908
01:01:38,450 --> 01:01:41,249
- Can I ask you something?
- Sure.

909
01:01:41,330 --> 01:01:45,529
When you married Gwen,
was it, in some small way,

910
01:01:45,569 --> 01:01:47,489
to get back at me?

911
01:01:47,529 --> 01:01:50,649
To show me what a wonderful
husband you would've been?

912
01:01:50,729 --> 01:01:53,929
It probably had
something to do with it.

913
01:01:54,009 --> 01:01:57,889
- People do such foolish things!
- Oh!

914
01:01:57,969 --> 01:02:01,249
Becky, I feel like
I have so much to tell you.

915
01:02:01,289 --> 01:02:04,209
When I first met Gwen,
I was still on the rebound.

916
01:02:04,289 --> 01:02:08,449
Oh! Thanks
for letting me talk.

917
01:02:08,529 --> 01:02:11,289
- A lot of this is my fault.
- No!

918
01:02:11,370 --> 01:02:14,769
If I hadn't turned you down,
misjudged you.

919
01:02:14,849 --> 01:02:19,089
I'm so lonely, Davis.
The men I date, it never works out.

920
01:02:19,169 --> 01:02:22,649
Most of them are just jerks.
They make up stories.

921
01:02:22,729 --> 01:02:25,689
They'll tell you anything
to get you into bed.

922
01:02:25,770 --> 01:02:28,209
Then there are
the guys like you,

923
01:02:28,289 --> 01:02:32,529
the kind you don't appreciate
when you have the chance.

924
01:02:34,449 --> 01:02:37,289
Thanks for
letting me talk.

925
01:03:21,449 --> 01:03:23,849
Oh, Davis.

926
01:04:12,409 --> 01:04:16,289
Oh, Becky,
I've wanted you for so long.

927
01:04:19,890 --> 01:04:22,329
Oh, Davis.

928
01:04:23,409 --> 01:04:27,529
Ah yes.
Oh, Davis.

929
01:04:27,609 --> 01:04:31,410
Oh yes.

930
01:04:31,489 --> 01:04:34,369
No! Wait!
Not like this.

931
01:04:34,449 --> 01:04:37,889
- Why?
- I can't! I can't be the other woman.

932
01:04:37,969 --> 01:04:41,329
If your marriage ends, it ends,
but not because of me.

933
01:04:41,369 --> 01:04:45,209
Can't you understand?
You're married!

934
01:05:17,290 --> 01:05:19,689
Come on, come on!

935
01:05:33,890 --> 01:05:37,170
How was your day?

936
01:05:37,249 --> 01:05:39,729
Oh, it was okay.

937
01:05:39,809 --> 01:05:42,409
I was just too tired to make
anything other than that.

938
01:05:42,449 --> 01:05:47,129
I brought some Chinese. I figured you'd
be exhausted from shopping with my mother.

939
01:05:47,209 --> 01:05:51,009
I get exhausted thinking about it.
Did you get a dress?

940
01:05:51,089 --> 01:05:53,129
